<paragraph id="1EF7A64B863461584BCCD1870D08DC44" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B9B789440893BACFBCB7825EF7BE1E85" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">
<taxonomicName id="0C47E4947D1F87E5617864CABEF84CA5" authorityName="D. Santos &amp; Buril" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ipomoea maranhensis" order="Solanales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maranhensis">
<emphasis id="DC168D7D15D9CEB67BBAD0466ACD1F4E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Ipomoea maranhensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs morphologically from 
<taxonomicName id="4A69C4E8ECD01B2B2CF10BD21EAF3D6C" genus="I." lsidName="I. burchellii" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" rank="species" species="burchellii">
<emphasis id="387E1D3F45938F7602BA329EEC5498F9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">I. burchellii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Meins. by its twining habit (vs. subshrubs), lanceolate (vs. oblong), long-acuminate (vs. acute) and densely sericeous (vs. hirsute) sepals.
</paragraph>
